  "response_text": "Depth-First Search (DFS) and Breadth-First Search (BFS) are two fundamental graph traversal algorithms used in computer science. They differ significantly in their approach to exploring nodes in a graph or tree structure.\n\n### Depth-First Search (DFS)\n\n**Approach:**\n- DFS explores as far down a branch as it can before backtracking.\n- It uses a stack (or recursion) to keep track of the next node to visit.\n- The algorithm chooses one child of the current node and explores it completely before moving on to the next child.\n\n**Key Characteristics:**\n- **Order of Visiting Nodes:** DFS visits nodes in a \"depth-first\" manner, meaning it goes deep into the graph before exploring siblings.\n- **Memory Usage:** DFS typically requires less memory than BFS because it only needs to store the path from the root to the current node.\n- **Cycle Detection:** DFS is often used for detecting cycles in graphs.\n- **Applications:** DFS is useful for problems",
